The bitter cold of the desert makes me feel high. And when the sun finally shines upon my face, it looks right through me as if I’m made of dust. 

1. 📷 @eliza_earle 
2 North Six Shooter
An old j-tree illustration. Pretty different than my work now, but also some distinct themes that have carried through ✨

Last year was unlike any other. It was wild and vibrant. Full of love. I felt my heart expand beyond the borders of its past. And it was fast. At times I felt like I was holding on for dear life, the ground whizzing and blurred beneath my feet. 

Here are a few little (some big) moments from 2022. Mostly about love, because it was a year of great love. (Fair warning)

1. Visiting the homeland.
2. Hanging with family and getting to see drew and my families as if they had been one all along. 
3. Goofing around with my sisters the day before the wedding making sure I remembered how to walk in wedges. So much excitement and anticipation. 
4. 💋 
5. Getting to share the magic of Canada with my sister Rhozzie. 
6. Selfies with Drew right after climbing hydrophobia in the Ghost. He took me by complete surprise and asked me to do forever with him. Not a soul in sight for miles on end, just how we like it. 
7. A magical backcountry hot spring adventure in Canada. 
8. Goofing off at the gym. One of those sweet little moments that make me smile.
9. Got a dirt bike! Let the desert adventures begin! (Just need a little more practice 😉)
10. Climbing La Esfinge with @a.little.wall.flower and climbing in the mountains with @followyourblitz 👯‍♀️ (Peru)

This meadow felt nostalgic even the first time I ever laid in it. Year after year, it turns into something new. The shapes of the cathedrals always shifting with the sun. 

Each season, stories bring us back here to share with friends over a beer or a picnic. It is a catalogue of all the dreamers before us and all ahead. 

30” x 22” Watercolor 
for @yosguns @ticklistmama 

#yosemite#cathedrals#yosemiteart#yosemitewatercolor#yosemitepainting#elcapmeadow#landscapesrtist#meadow#middlecathedral#highercathedralspire #lowercathedral#pastels#watercolor#archespaper

From start to finish, so much goes into these paintings. After many attempts to capture the essence of this incredible place, I’m glad I took the time to truly let the cathedrals and meadow unfold. Paintings are on their own timeline, and we just have to have the patience and trust to honor that. I’ll admit, it’s challenging, especially amidst the fast-pace demand of this platform. There is so much pressure to produce and share something new. Sometimes it feels like the slow labors of love can’t keep up. But I value this process so I’ll keep chugging along at whatever pace the art dictates.❤️

On another note, prints are live on the site! 

I printed these on the highest quality Hahnemühle paper (100% cotton) to replicate the look and feel of the original. The live edge of the painting is also preserved in the print creating an incredibly close reproduction. (See more on my site) ✨

Process photos by @_drew_smith_

^ Soaking in that last sliver of light in el cap meadow a few years back. Lately I’ve been more busy, less on the move. I’m investing in and creating space to learn more about my craft… something I’ve deeply wanted but found hard to do on the road. It’s exciting but It also feels like a harness. What about the fuel for the craft? It doesn’t feel like there’s much time for both. At least not right now. I’m practicing the whole big picture thing. Something I haven’t ever been all that good at …. I’ve lived my life chasing a thought or a whim. It’s worked out pretty well so far, but I’m trying to find a little more balance. I’ll report back. 

Photo by @eliza_earle

👋 It’s been a while! I’ve been focusing on a big website overhaul (lots on the back end), experimenting with new mediums, and training for an upcoming climbing expedition. 

Over the years, I’ve learned that creative work requires constant adaptability and for me the only way to keep it sustainable is to switch focus to other parts of my business and life, knowing that the “art” part will always come back when the time is right. 

Like clockwork, the summer wildflowers did ignite something in me and I recently painted a few small floral pieces of the hills above the city (SLC). 

As I prepare to head into the mountains soon, I already feel that little fire start to grow into something fierce and am so excited to see where it all leads; creatively, physically and spiritually.

10” x 10” prints available on my website rhiannonklee.com 🌟

A few snippets from my journal in Pakistan - sharing the ups and downs. All beautiful in their own way. 

~ Aug 5 ~

Feeling the buzz from our climb yesterday and running on just a few hours of sleep. I thought I’d feel exhausted but I feel energized. I collect flowers on the hillside above camp. There are so many varieties in just one area: vibrant purple flowers we think are geraniums, red blooms with spikey stalks…. so many forget-me-nots!! They make me think of Drew. I place a few in my journal between sheets of tissue paper, preserving them between the pages like grandma taught me.

~ Aug 6 ~

 I slept 12 hrs last night and am feel refreshed. I spent the morning cleaning my tent, stretching and then walking through the cool streams until I found a little beach in the curve of the river. The water winds around my body and I lay down with my toes in the water. Wet gravel presses into my skin, and into my left cheek. One hazy eye looks through eyelashes at the massive granites points that surround me. I smile as I feel my skin bake under the sun.

~ Aug 8 ~

I feel so sad. The energy is sucked from my body. I try to preserve my sense of peace by spending a lot of solo time. But today it is harder to shake the feeling. I haven’t felt this hollow in a while. Laying in the sunshine helps a little. I remember what a sensitive being I am.

Reminiscing on some special moments in Pakistan: 

1. Our guide Illyas’ wife at her home in the village of Kanday.
2. Jeep ride en route to Hushe, our launching point for the mountains! 
3. Steph and Thomas so tiny against the backdrop of K7
4. Nail painting party! It was just such a fun light day with lots of silly antics, singing and playing 💫
5. The gorgeous K7
6. Ussman, our very kind cook.
7. Steph topping out the spire under K6
8. Curious children peering into my tent.
9. Teachers in the Hushe valley, all of whom have earned their masters degree through the @iqrafund and are setting new standards for women’s education in rural Pakistan! 
10. Jeep driver (didn’t catch his name) chatting with some locals as we pass through a small village.

Finally working in oils!!!! This is just the under painting where I’m working out composition, and the colors are rather random. I haven’t painted with oils since college and I’ve been dreaming of this moment for a while. Last fall I took a university course to reacquaint myself with the medium. There’s something so kinetic and energizing about painting standing up, moving the brush all over the canvas and making marks with a little more abandon than I dare to with watercolor.
